  <!-- uPVC — text LEFT, images RIGHT -->
  <div style="margin-bottom: 1.2rem;">
    <div class="research-flex-row" style="display: flex; gap: 1.8rem; align-items: flex-start;">
      <div style="flex: 1; min-width: 0;">
        <h4 class="research-paper-title">Impact Behaviour of Pressurised uPVC Pipes</h4>
        <p>
          This study examines the low-velocity lateral impact response of water-pressurised
          <strong>uPVC pipes</strong> under <strong>both-ends-clamped</strong> and <strong>one-clamped-one-roller</strong> support conditions, across
          four drop heights (1.0–2.75 m), using a locally built <strong>ESP32-based pressure and velocity measuring unit</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Clamped supports yielded up to <strong>6.34%</strong> higher peak contact force. Internal pressure reached <strong>3063 kPa</strong> at 2.75
          m drop. FEA matched experiment within ~14%.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--global-text-color-light);">
          <em>In Preparation, 2025</em>
        </p>
